My question to you guys is how do you make the small details on your characters,logo, etc. look so good and distinguised enough to tell what it is? <br>
 <br>
I'm having trouble with this dark elf warrior named Shima that I am working on and I can't seem to add belts to his clothing, I can't get the belt straps to look like belt straps since the picture isn't very big. The belts I drew on his arm look like cheap squares with a rectangle going through them. i'm using a regualr 2h pencil but I'm having trouble adding the detail, not to mention the shading that is need to make it look 3 dimensional lol.<br>
<br>
In other words, how do you add small details to drawings on paper? Your sight is limited because its hard to see and you have limited space as well. <br>
<br>
The character's  arm  is similar to  Vash the stampede's , but its not robotic, just covered in leather with belt straps on it. I'm so bad at using photoshop 7. besides I would need to d/l it to this computer anyway.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   - thanks <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=linglingbolt>linglingbolt</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://liquid2k.com/lingbolt/spidey10x10.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/26/03 9:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5695.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.blindcrocodile.net/banners/willowhead60x60.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Adding detail</span><hr size=1> The fact is there's a limit to how much detail you can squeeze into a small area.  Focus on light and shadow and overall forms for small drawings.  A pair of lines and a square is enough to tell people &quot;This is a belt, that's a belt buckle.&quot;  People are smart that way.  Save the detail for close-ups.  Do lots of close-up sketches of details that you feel are important, just don't do them on a full-body drawing.<br>
<br>
Choosing what to leave out is just as important as choosing what to draw.  I have some perfect examples from the Trigun manga if you want to see.  I'm just not in the mood to post them now <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ...<br>
<br>
Case in point: When drawing an eye from far away, I usually just draw an arc and a dot.  From close up, I draw shading in the iris, eyelashes, lacrimals, creases, reflections, etc, etc...  There's a huge difference in the amount of detail, but it works.  It's the same for everything. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
PS, a logo should probably be as simple as possible.  I mean, check out the PK logo.  It's... the word PolyKarbon!  With a blue outline!  Not a lot of detail there, not much to worry about, instantly identifiable.  The best logos are the simple ones. <p>-----------------<br>
-Lingling</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=linglingbolt>linglingbolt</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://liquid2k.com/lingbolt/spidey10x10.gif" BORDER=0> at: 8/26/03 9:12 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dangercabbit>DangerCabbit</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/26/03 10:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5695.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Adding detail</span><hr size=1> try using a very sharp, hard lead pencil, say an H or HB. And/or use bigger paper.<br>
<br>
practice drawing belts and boots, and other accessories from photos or real life, but draw them real small and just practice making the details as sharp as possible <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=revanto@polykarbonbbs>Revanto</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/26/03 11:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5695.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Adding detail</span><hr size=1> Well, if the output is going to be digital then you just draw the basic look and then draw any difficult details much larger on a separate piece of paper. When you have them scanned, just shrink the detail pics and composite them on your final image.<br>
<br>
Easy!<br>
<br>
Good Luck<br>
